column1: так что ошибаются все. кроме тех

;я чуть было не опустила руки . это было моей мечтой , так этого хотела , так ждала , но пожалела . зачем мне все это нужно ? что будет дальше ? 🤷🏻‍♀️ . закупила десятки метров ткани , фурнитуру , отремонтировала швейную машинку , настроила оверлок . загорелась этой идеей шить детский текстиль . но появилась неуверенность , страх . а вдруг не получится ? а если не будет заказов😨 ? . всё . стоп . ну не получится и что ? не конец света же ? но в голове появилась едва заметная фраза : « все будет , все решим » . может всё-таки не стоит ? может это не моё ? - сопротивлялась я. фраза звучала все отчётливей « все будет , все решим » . и тут я узнала этот голос . это же папины слова ! он всегда так говорил в детстве , спокойно « все хорошо , все решим » . и когда были проблемы с математикой в универе , и период , когда очень хотелось новые джинсы , а денег не было даже на хлеб . и много ещё всего.. но проходило время и все разрешалось ! . и мой папа🙏🏻 , мой ангел хранитель , сейчас наблюдает за мной сверху , и в трудные моменты я слышу его слова « все будет , все решим » . даже если что-то идёт не так , как вам хотелось бы , главное не опускать руки . опустив их тогда , вы бы не видели меня здесь сейчас , не шила бы я для ваших деток👼🏻💕 . так что ошибаются все . кроме тех , конечно , кто ничего не делает😊 ну что скажите , девочки , всё проходит ? все ведь разрешается ? column1: 132035;instagram;2018-11-28 17:46:39;TRUE;;"after listening to karen rain’s interview yesterday and sharing some of my feelings on it in my last post
column2: i honestly don’t feel compelled to share anything light-hearted or movement related today.

column1: i’m not going to try and put a positive spin on what i feel. instead i’m going to sit with it for a while
maybe movement stuff tomorrow. for now
life is going to kick us all when we’re down. hard. there’s no way to pretty that up.❤️

when we turn people’s pain into a “bright-side” story ... that’s our own fear of being overwhelmed by painful or devastating emotions. (aka: the spiritual by-pass). worst of all: it’s abandoning & shaming to people in pain. let’s try not to do that. 💗

of course we all want to help! me too - it’s my first instinct! but one of the hardest things about being human: is not being able to relieve someone else’s emotional suffering. ❤️ but being present is the next best thing. .

column4: so here it goes. there has been lots of confusion and backlash at the #metoo movement. it happened very fast and left older generations wondering what women were complaining about. images we all grew up with made it seem ok for men to do whatever they like because all women needed a man...right? wrong. many factors have changed the family dynamic and women have had the most metamorphosis. men are in need of catching up and this politically charged climate leads to lots of arguing and little discussion. bitterness comes from arguing

column1: مدت زیادی از موجی که در آن ده‌ها تن از زنان هالیوود، تهیه‌کننده سرشناس «هاروی واینستین» را متهم به آزار و تعرض جنسی کردند نگذشته است. نام چهره‌هایی چون گوئنت پالترو، آنجلینا جولی، اشلی جاد، لیا سیدو و... در میان نام بیش از چهل زنی دیده می‌شود که اعلام کردند توسط واینستین مورد آزار قرار گرفته‌اند. مجله نیویورکر در گزارشی لیستی دقیق از اسامی و تجربه‌های این افراد منتشر کرده است. نیویورک تایمز نیز افشا کرده که چگونه واینستین توانسته است برای سال‌ها تعرضاتش را پشت پرده نگاه دارد. زنانی که ادعای خود در اینباره را علنی کرده‌اند اکنون در دنیا به عنوان نمادهای شجاعت شناخته می‌شوند و هر روایت و افشاگری بر زشتی موفقیت سالیان این تهیه‌کننده می‌افزاید.

شجاعت متهم‌کنندگان واینستین الهام‌بخش کاربران فضاهای مجازی شده است تا با استفاده از هشتگ #metoo (من هم) تجربیات خود از آزار، تعرض و تجاوز را به اشتراک بگذارند. با وجود اینکه اغلب رسانه‌ها امتیاز برجسته کردن این جنبش را به آلیسا میلانو، بازیگر هالیوود می‌دهند، ماهنامه ابونی بر این نکته تاکید می‌کند که تارانا برک، فعال اجتماعی رنگین‌پوست، ده سال پیش این کمپین را راه‌اندازی کرده بوده است.

مساله همینجاست، در فضای صحبت از فرهنگ تجاوز مشکلی اساسی به چشم می‌خورد؛ افراد به حاشیه رانده‌شده، زنان رنگین‌پوست، زنان طبقه فرودست، زنان بدون اوراق هویتی، افراد دوجنسی و ... به صورتی مضاعف در معرض آزارهای جنسی هستند. از آنجا که در هفته‌های گذشته مقاله‌ها و گزارشات فراوانی درباره این معضل منتشر شده و افراد بسیاری با به اشتراک گذاشتن تجربه‌های خود برای نشان دادن فراگیری تعرض جنسی تلاش کرده‌اند، توجه به این نکته ضروری است که تا چه اندازه هویت و موقعیت هر قربانی با میزان توانایی او برای شکایت از یک کمپانی، مطلع کردن یک مسئول و یا حتی استفاده از هشتگ «من هم» در فضای مجازی مرتبط است. زنان جوامع محروم بسیار بیشتر در معرض آزارهای جنسی هستند و برای اثبات ادعاهای خود با موانع بسیار دشوارتری روبرو می‌شوند.  آمار سی‌دی‌سی (مرکز جهانی پیشگیری و مقابله با بیماری) نشان می‌دهد ۳۳ درصد از زنان چندرگه، ۲۷ درصد از زنان بومی آمریکا و ۲۲ درصد از زنان سیاهپوست قربانی تجاوز بوده‌اند. این عدد برای زنان سفیدپوست ۱۹ است. (ادامه متن در کامنت)

مدت زیادی از موجی که در آن ده‌ها تن از زنان هالیوود، تهیه‌کننده سرشناس «هاروی واینستین» را متهم به آزار و تعرض جنسی کردند نگذشته است. نام چهره‌هایی چون گوئنت پالترو، آنجلینا جولی، اشلی جاد، لیا سیدو و... در میان نام بیش از چهل زنی دیده می‌شود که اعلام کردند توسط واینستین مورد آزار قرار گرفته‌اند. مجله نیویورکر در گزارشی لیستی دقیق از اسامی و تجربه‌های این افراد منتشر کرده است. نیویورک تایمز نیز افشا کرده که چگونه واینستین توانسته است برای سال‌ها تعرضاتش را پشت پرده نگاه دارد. زنانی که ادعای خود در اینباره را علنی کرده‌اند اکنون در دنیا به عنوان نمادهای شجاعت شناخته می‌شوند و هر روایت و افشاگری بر زشتی موفقیت سالیان این تهیه‌کننده می‌افزاید.

شجاعت متهم‌کنندگان واینستین الهام‌بخش کاربران فضاهای مجازی شده است تا با استفاده از هشتگ  (من هم) تجربیات خود از آزار، تعرض و تجاوز را به اشتراک بگذارند. با وجود اینکه اغلب رسانه‌ها امتیاز برجسته کردن این جنبش را به آلیسا میلانو، بازیگر هالیوود می‌دهند، ماهنامه ابونی بر این نکته تاکید می‌کند که تارانا برک، فعال اجتماعی رنگین‌پوست، ده سال پیش این کمپین را راه‌اندازی کرده بوده است.

شجاعت شناخته می‌شوند و هر روایت و افشاگری بر زشتی موفقیت سالیان این تهیه‌کننده می‌افزاید . شجاعت متهم‌کنندگان واینستین الهام‌بخش کاربران فضاهای مجازی شده است تا با استفاده از هشتگ ( من هم ) تجربیات خود از آزار، تعرض و تجاوز را به اشتراک بگذارند . با وجود اینکه اغلب رسانه‌ها امتیاز برجسته کردن این جنبش را به آلیسا میلانو، بازیگر هالیوود می‌دهند، ماهنامه ابونی بر این نکته تاکید می‌کند که تارانا برک، فعال اجتماعی رنگین‌پوست، ده سال پیش این کمپین را راه‌اندازی کرده بوده است . مساله همینجاست، در فضای صحبت از فرهنگ تجاوز مشکلی اساسی به چشم می‌خورد؛ افراد به حاشیه رانده‌شده، زنان رنگین‌پوست، زنان طبقه فرودست، زنان بدون اوراق هویتی، افراد دوجنسی و ... به صورتی مضاعف در معرض آزارهای جنسی هستند . از آنجا که در هفته‌های گذشته مقاله‌ها و گزارشات فراوانی درباره این معضل منتشر شده و افراد بسیاری با به اشتراک گذاشتن تجربه‌های خود برای نشان دادن فراگیری تعرض جنسی تلاش کرده‌اند، توجه به این نکته ضروری است که تا چه اندازه هویت و موقعیت هر قربانی با میزان توانایی او برای شکایت از یک کمپانی، مطلع کردن یک مسئول و یا حتی استفاده از هشتگ « من هم » در فضای مجازی مرتبط است . زنان جوامع محروم بسیار بیشتر در معرض آزارهای جنسی هستند و برای اثبات ادعاهای خود با موانع بسیار دشوارتری روبرو می‌شوند . آمار سی‌دی‌سی ( مرکز جهانی پیشگیری و مقابله با بیماری ) نشان می‌دهد ۳۳ درصد از زنان چندرگه، ۲۷ درصد از زنان بومی آمریکا و ۲۲ درصد از زنان سیاهپوست قربانی تجاوز بوده‌اند . این عدد برای زنان سفیدپوست ۱۹ است . column1: 132198;instagram;2018-11-28 14:36:55;FALSE;"the valomerkki campaign has raised awareness about the faults of club culture and nightlife revealing how common and widespread multifaceted harassment and discrimination are. as event organizer also x-rust operates in the local nightlife and we want our effect on the operational culture to be positive.
when we organize events as an association and community
column4: usually in co-operation with the representatives of the venue. simultaneously many members of our board and organization altogether are deejays
column7: participate in the organizing of events in some other role and of course go to events. hence the issue affects us and our activities a great deal even though we hardly ever physically operate in traditional club settings.

column1: we want to operate in a way
column2: that can withstand even the closest scrutiny. we do not accept any kind of harrassment or discrimination in any of our activities
column3: from anyone. we take the comfort and well-being of our customers
column4: artists and event organizers seriously and intervene with any issues without delay.

column1: in the future we will take better care that we also communicate these views and inform the public clearly about the actions we take against harassment and discrimination.
we support the valomerkki campaign and take the questions it has raised and demands it has made seriously in our activities.
on behalf of the x-rust organization

column1: from first hand experience i know that when someone tells you it will be ok
column4: punch them in the face 😡. i mean flat out! do you ever feel like that?

column1: i also know that to a degree they are right. that’s possibly as i’m picking them up off the floor! 😬
i also know that it took me a very
column2: very long time with lots of attempts that didn’t quite go to plan to take back control and start to believe in me and create the life i wanted. i’m talking about how you step into being who you really want to be after therapy or counselling.

column1: yes it’s a different life than i perhaps thought and that’s alright. i just wish i’d been able to take back control sooner.

column1: 132216;instagram;2018-11-28 14:50:37;FALSE;"evelyn sharma turns into a social entrepreneur for women influencers
the ‘yaariyan’ actress evelyn sharma speaks about her views on the #metoo movement that has currently hit bollywood’s shores
column2: she speaks about how she is currently focusing on giving women in the entertainment industry a safe backing by turning into a social entrepreneur with her new venture
column3: her very own image development company which caters to women influencers.

column2: who started her career as an international model in 2008 and debuted in her first bollywood film in 2012
column3: says: “i’ve been in this industry for a long time and have experienced a lot of disrespectful behavior towards women. i left the talent agency that managed me in the start of my film career because of that reason and since then hired and trained my own team. it’s a common thing to say that a girl (or boy) needs a godfather to make it in the industry
column4: but i would like to differ. i think it needs talent
column6: and a big portion of courage to stick to your own beliefs. i never had a godfather
column7: however i make a great living off the kind of projects i choose and get to work with amazing people. there will always be trolls trying to stand in your way
column8: but that’s no reason to give up! the whole world will tell you what path to take
column10: and whom to fraternize with - but who are you and what are your dreams? i’ve discovered being true to yourself is where real happiness awaits you and had the honor to encourage others by sharing my story of overcoming struggles with identity at various events
column11: like the us president’s national prayer breakfast in washington d.c.” witnessing all the change this movement is bringing
column12: she came across an idea of how she could better the situation by helping women influencers and celebrities
column13: that’s when her idea was born. she decided to build a strong team of professionals for herself and for her friends in the industry to help them grow and release her full potential. she believes that we are all in the process of growing and realizing our own potential
column15: we are all a “work in progress”

column1: 132227;instagram;2018-11-28 14:01:43;FALSE;"there are a number of root causes that lead to violence against women and children
column2: here are some of the leading ones:

column1: 1. misconstrued cultural beliefs - no culture advocates for violence against women however
column2: people often misconstrue their cultural practices to fit a mould that best serves their personal agenda. an example of this is the traditional practice of ukuthwalwa which has been used as a guise to force young women into marriage.

column1: 2. learned behaviour - being exposed to violence in a home or community teaches a person that violence is okay. research has found that men who have experienced or witnessed violence in their childhood  are more likely to be violent towards their partner.
3. financial dependence - this is often a trap for women and children. south african has a disproportionate number of women who are uneducated and unemployed
column2: leaving them little option but to stay in a cycle of violence. the need to spread awareness about ways to seek help can begin to break down the staggering numbers of women in a situation like this.

column1: 4. alcohol abuse - alcohol abuse has been linked to all forms of interpersonal violence. a 2009 study found that 67% of men had consumed alcohol before abusing their partners. ‘i was drunk’ is often used by men to shed accountability for violence towards their partners. gender norms often result in men seeking to assert their masculinity through risk-talking behaviour such as alcohol abuse and violence.
this is not an exhaustive list of causes
column2: but is the beginnings of creating a broader picture. understanding where violence against women comes from will help guide the conversation towards how we can put an end to it. •

column1: 132248;instagram;2018-11-28 14:09:25;FALSE;"""women themselves are greatest enemies of womenkind"" - anonymous. (aurat hi aurat ki dushman hoti hai). i have heard this statement since my childhood from fellow women as well as men around. and i started believing it as the only truth. i
column2: as a child was injected and infused with this idea which i gathered from the people around everywhere. hence
column3: giving an idea of being competitive and jealous  that was a byproduct of mindset of being ""better"" than the women around.

column1: here comes one genuine question. why do i need to let down my own kind to rise above and further
column2: by calling my fellow ""competition "" a bitch to mark myself superior?
why is that even a competition?

column1: take these cases for instance- ""your man cheated on you and  you targeted other woman for being in his life and call her a whore for doing that
column2: you plan all kinds of revenge against her
column3: instead of turning to the man in question.

column1: your distant cousin's daughter just began to model
column2: posted her  pictures from recent boudoir shoot she had and man she looked beautiful in it.

column1: but you chose to spread all kind of rumours surrounding her character.
your neighbour's daughter is the sole bread winner of the family
column3: and you sit in your group to gossip about it. ""

کانال تلگرام:";خطی می کشم برای آن ۲ زنی که هر هفته به دلیل خشونت در انگلستان می میرد . برای هر ۱ دختر از ۳ دختری که اولین تجربه جنسی اش، تجاوز است . برای هر زنی که باید سکوت کند و صدایش به جایی نمی رسد . من خطی می کشم زیرا که سال ٢٠١٧ است . زیرا که خشونت علیه زنان تنها موضوعی زنانه نیست . خطی می کشم برای پایان دادن به رفتار کسانی که وانمود می کنند اتفاق نیفتاده . برای آنهایی که خشونت آنلاین را تجربه می کنند . برای آن ۲۰۰ میلیون زنی که قربانی ناقص سازی اندام جنسی هستند . خطی می کشم زیرا که بدن هر زنی فقط و فقط متعلق به خود اوست . برای هر زنی که می گوید “ من هم ” etoo خطی می کشم برای آن زنانی که شجاعت دارند و برمی خیزند . من خطی می کشم زیرا که می دانم نباید سکوت کنم . بمناسبت ۲۵ نوامبر روز جهانی بارزه_با_خشونت_علیه_زنان 🚩انقلاب ایران یک است . به انقلاب زنانه بپیوندید . وانان_کمونیست پیامگیر تلگرام jktamas کانال تلگرام : ;[('خطی'

column1: дело было так: аттракцион 'башня террора' - фишка в том что все сидят в бешеном лифте в клетке

column1: я в принципе баба отнюдь не робкого десятка
column2: я и с паршютом прыгала и по небоскребам лазила. но сев на этот аттракцион от неожиданности переконила не по-детски и во время первого 'падения' лифта я схватила парня сидящего с лева от меня за его мужское достоинство! мне почему-то показалось что у нас будут индивидуальные порочни по сторонам
column3: а как выяснилось держаться можно было только за поперечную перекладину.

132333;instagram;2018-11-28 13:03:18;FALSE;"it's moments like today that i know why i created footsteps to inspire ❤️ i'm in singapore for a flash 1.5 days. this morning i headed to the singapore girls' school. it's a school but not a school per say. it's a fairly high security place. the girls here are either caught in the criminal system or have protection orders. most have faced terrible violence in their short lifetimes - physical
column3: psychological to name a few. many self harm or act out as a way to cope. the singapore girls' school is a way for these girls to have a second chance at life. a big focus is given on healing
column4: restoration and reintegration back into their communities. today i had the honor of sharing my story with these girls. and i truly mean an honor. watching these young faces absorb my ordeal and register that like them
column5: i had faced similar life traumas as a child and as a young woman. and that i had made it through
column6: that healing is possible and that they can go for their dreams 🌟

column1: instead of just talking at them
column2: i also spent time answering their questions. blown away by the depth of emotion
column3: thought and understanding in their questions...

column1: what did you do to heal?""
making a difference in the world is hard
column2: do you face resistance or people who want to stop you?""

column1: today i gave a group of deeply traumatized girls a reason to heal and hope for a better life. and guess what
column2: most of them want to come and run with me. what a great reason for me to come back to singapore 👍

column1: i don't have any photos to share yet from this morning as they need clearance first. this pic is with the really sweet gift the girls made for me 🌸

column1: إن الاحتجاجات الأخيرة وحملة على الإنترنت في أيرلندا في أعقاب محاكمة الاغتصاب التي وصف فيها ثونغ مراهقاً قام بالاغتصاب هي مثال آخر على غضب النساء الذي يغذي العمل والتضامن، ففي الساعات التي تلت الإبلاغ عن القضية في وسائل الإعلام، نشرت مئات النساء صوراً لملابسهن الداخلية على وسائل التواصل الاجتماعي، وأرسلن تغريدة #thisisnotconsent لإظهار معارضتهن لإلقاء اللوم على الضحية.

في أيرلندا الشمالية، أثارت تبرئة أربعة من لاعبي أولغهام بتهمة الاغتصاب وغيره من الجرائم الجنسية مناقشات واسعة النطاق حول مدى ملاءمة العمليات القانونية ومعاملتهم لمقدمي الشكاوى، وأدت الاحتجاجات التي جرت على الصعيد الوطني إلى إجراء استعراض مستقل لمعالجة حالات العنف الجنسي ومعاملة مقدمي الشكاوى.

إن الاتجاه العام هو أننا نسير في الاتجاه الصحيح، حيث لم تعد الحكومات الأوروبية تتجاهل أصوات النساء اللاتي يطالبن بالحقوق والإنصاف، وعلى الرغم من قيام النساء بحملة ضد الاغتصاب لسنوات، فقد ضمنت حملة #metoo مساحة للحوار، مما جعل أصواتهم أقوى.

تتطلب اتفاقية اسطنبول (وهي معاهدة لحقوق الإنسان صدَّقت عليها غالبية البلدان الأوروبية) من الدول تجريم جميع الأفعال غير الموافق عليها ذات الطبيعة الجنسية، وإن تغيير القوانين لن يقضي على الاغتصاب لكنها خطوة حاسمة على طول الطريق، كما أنها تبعث برسالة قوية للغاية حول نوع المجتمع الذي نرغب في العيش فيه: حيث نريد أن نكون في دولة متحررين من الاغتصاب، حيث يحترم الجميع الاستقلالية الجنسية وسلامة الجسد ويقدرونه.

إن الاحتجاجات الأخيرة وحملة على الإنترنت في أيرلندا في أعقاب محاكمة الاغتصاب التي وصف فيها ثونغ مراهقاً قام بالاغتصاب هي مثال آخر على غضب النساء الذي يغذي العمل والتضامن، ففي الساعات التي تلت الإبلاغ عن القضية في وسائل الإعلام، نشرت مئات النساء صوراً لملابسهن الداخلية على وسائل التواصل الاجتماعي، وأرسلن تغريدة #thisisnotconsent لإظهار معارضتهن لإلقاء اللوم على الضحية.

إن الاحتجاجات الأخيرة وحملة على الإنترنت في أيرلندا في أعقاب محاكمة الاغتصاب التي وصف فيها ثونغ مراهقاً قام بالاغتصاب هي مثال آخر على غضب النساء الذي يغذي العمل والتضامن، ففي الساعات التي تلت الإبلاغ عن القضية في وسائل الإعلام، نشرت مئات النساء صوراً لملابسهن الداخلية على وسائل التواصل الاجتماعي، وأرسلن تغريدة  لإظهار معارضتهن لإلقاء اللوم على الضحية.

في أيرلندا الشمالية، أثارت تبرئة أربعة من لاعبي أولغهام بتهمة الاغتصاب وغيره من الجرائم الجنسية مناقشات واسعة النطاق حول مدى ملاءمة العمليات القانونية ومعاملتهم لمقدمي الشكاوى، وأدت الاحتجاجات التي جرت على الصعيد الوطني إلى إجراء استعراض مستقل لمعالجة حالات العنف الجنسي ومعاملة مقدمي الشكاوى.

إن الاتجاه العام هو أننا نسير في الاتجاه الصحيح، حيث لم تعد الحكومات الأوروبية تتجاهل أصوات النساء اللاتي يطالبن بالحقوق والإنصاف، وعلى الرغم من قيام النساء بحملة ضد الاغتصاب لسنوات، فقد ضمنت حملة  مساحة للحوار، مما جعل أصواتهم أقوى.

تتطلب اتفاقية اسطنبول (وهي معاهدة لحقوق الإنسان صدَّقت عليها غالبية البلدان الأوروبية) من الدول تجريم جميع الأفعال غير الموافق عليها ذات الطبيعة الجنسية، وإن تغيير القوانين لن يقضي على الاغتصاب لكنها خطوة حاسمة على طول الطريق، كما أنها تبعث برسالة قوية للغاية حول نوع المجتمع الذي نرغب في العيش فيه: حيث نريد أن نكون في دولة متحررين من الاغتصاب، حيث يحترم الجميع الاستقلالية الجنسية وسلامة الجسد ويقدرونه.

column1: 132405;instagram;2018-11-28 11:34:32;FALSE;"हम लोग अक्सर अपने लिए कुछ न कुछ करते ही रहते हैं। परन्तु ऐसा बहुत कभी कभी ही होता है जब हम दूसरों के बारे में सोचते भी हों। या तो हम लोग किसी मंदिर के दर्शन करने जा रहे हो
column2: तब हम दान देते हैं मंदिरों में
column3: या फिर उस मंदिर के बहार खड़े किसी गरीब को दान देते हैं। लेकिन सिर्फ यही 2 अवसर नहीं होते दान-पुण्य करने के। जयपुर की ngo जीवन अर्थ फाउंडेशन दिनांक 9 दिसंबर रविवार के दिन जयपुर में ही स्थित अलिआवास गाऊं में एक कैंप (हेल्थ कैंप health camp) लगाने जा रहा है जिसमे e.n.t. स्पेशलिस्ट से ले कर अन्य अलग अलग डॉक्टरों का प्रबंध करवाया जा रहा है। इस कैंप को सही तरह से करवाने के लिए
column4: हम आपके सहयोग की आशा रखते हैं। हमें उम्मीद है कि आप अपना सहयोग अवश्ये देंगे। कृपया हमारी वेबसाइट www.jeevanarth.org पर अपनी इच्छा अनुसार दान कर सकते हैं एवं दान कि प्रक्रिया को और आसान बनाने के लिए आप हमे paytm (8104107086) पर भी दान दे सकते हैं। आपका धन्यवाद

132448;instagram;2018-11-28 10:37:09;FALSE;"qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv
column2: completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

column1: that’s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him “we can take it.” no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it’s a little thing
column2: just part of the story we are all interacting with.

column1: the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters
column2: then it’s easy to come along for the ride. there’s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they’re both just characters on the television.

column1: that’s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it’s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it’s that we’ve lost the capacity to treat civics
column3: and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters
column4: so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

column1: 132451;instagram;2018-11-28 10:38:32;FALSE;"today i spoke up - i said what needed to be said. it left me shaking
column2: anxious & nervous. i am not good at confrontation - if i can avoid it i will. but today i felt so angry that i had no choice. you see i listened to a podcast yesterday between karen rain & @jbrownyoga - it was a moving
column3: honest & brave conversation. she spoke powerfully on the subject of abuse
column4: of trauma & of the dangerous dance of toxic power that has happened in yoga studios across the world. she also challenged j on his white male privilege & pushed him to educate himself on gender equality
column5: consent & trauma. they both handled it with grace & compassion. sure it got uncomfortable but the truth isn’t always comfortable & if we can’t be ok with that discomfort then we have no right to call ourselves yogis.

column1: her story is profound. the trauma she felt was so huge that not only did she have to leave her lineage but also the practice of yoga. i thought about that today & wept. the thought of not being able to practice yoga anymore because it was too triggering breaks my heart. i’ve been following these conversations & blogs for a while now but to hear her speak floored me.
so i spoke up. i don’t know if my words will be heard. maybe they will
column2: maybe they won’t. in my anxiety afterwards i could only do one thing - step onto my mat & breathe. in that moment i thought of every woman or man who has been abused & i felt so sad. at the same time though i felt my own strength
column3: emboldened by my words. so to anyone who has suffered at the hands of abuse i want you all to know that i see you
column4: i hear you & i believe you. my promise to you is this :- if i ever witness words or actions that to me are sexist
column6: violent & abusive in any way; i shall speak up. i shall speak up in truth & honesty. because it is through silence that we are complicit & no more will i be silenced.

column5: consent & trauma. they both handled it with grace & compassion. sure it got uncomfoable but the truth isn’t always comfoable & if we can’t be ok with that discomfo then we have no right to call ourselves yogis.

column1: her story is profound. the trauma she felt was so huge that not only did she have to leave her lineage but also the practice of yoga. i thought about that today & wept. the thought of not being able to practice yoga anymore because it was too triggering breaks my hea. i’ve been following these conversations & blogs for a while now but to hear her speak floored me.
so i spoke up. i don’t know if my words will be heard. maybe they will
column2: maybe they won’t. in my anxiety afterwards i could only do one thing - step onto my mat & breathe. in that moment i thought of every woman or man who has been abused & i felt so sad. at the same time though i felt my own strength
column3: emboldened by my words. so to anyone who has suffered at the hands of abuse i want you all to know that i see you
column4: i hear you & i believe you. my promise to you is this :- if i ever witness words or actions that to me are sexist
column6: violent & abusive in any way; i shall speak up. i shall speak up in truth & honesty. because it is through silence that we are complicit & no more will i be silenced.

column1: we had five years left to cry in
news guy wept and told us
cried so much his face was wet
then i knew he was not lying
my brain hurt like a warehouse
it had no room to spare
i had to cram so many things
i never thought i'd need so many people
a girl my age went off her head
if the black hadn't a-pulled her off
i think she would have killed them
a soldier with a broken arm
fixed his stare to the wheels of a cadillac
a cop knelt and kissed the feet of a priest
and a queer threw up at the sight of that
i think i saw you in an ice-cream parlour
drinking milk shakes cold and long
smiling and waving and looking so fine
don't think you knew you were in this song
and it was cold and it rained
so i felt like an actor
and i wanted to get back there

column1: it’s important that you are ready to answer your kids’ questions as they come up

column1: 132540;instagram;2018-11-28 06:23:26;FALSE;"#16daysofactivism against women abuse and gender based violence.
how did the 16 days of activism come about? the mirabal sisters
column2: political activists whose deaths were commemorated with the establishment of the international day for the elimination of violence against women. on 25 november 1960
column5: three political activists who actively opposed the cruelty and systematic violence of the trujillo dictatorship in the dominican republic
column6: were clubbed to death and dumped at the bottom of a cliff by trujillo’s secret police. the mirabal sisters became symbols of the feminist resistance
column7: and in commemoration of their deaths 25 november was declared international day for the elimination of violence against women in latin america in 1980. this international day was formally recognised by the united nations in 1999. in june 1991
column8: the centre for women’s global leadership (cwgl)
column9: alongside participants of the first women’s global institute on women
column11: called for a global campaign of 16 days of activism against gender-based violence. the 16 days begins with the international day for the elimination of violence against women and ends with international human rights day on 10 december– highlighting that violence against women is a fundamental violation of human rights. why does this matter? violence against women continues to occur at an alarming scale in every country in the world. too often it is accepted as normal behaviour and the global culture of discrimination against women allows violence to occur with impunity. recent movements such as #metoo and #timesup have propelled this issue onto the global stage.

column11: called for a global campaign of 16 days of activism against gender-based violence. the 16 days begins with the international day for the elimination of violence against women and ends with international human rights day on 10 december– highlighting that violence against women is a fundamental violation of human rights. why does this matter? violence against women continues to occur at an alarming scale in every country in the world. too often it is accepted as normal behaviour and the global culture of discrimination against women allows violence to occur with impunity. recent movements such as  and  have propelled this issue onto the global stage.

column1: 132568;instagram;2018-11-28 07:03:26;FALSE;mari beylerian was an armenian feminist who died in the armenian genocide. during her time in alexandria she taught at a local armenian school and between 1902-1903 she published the artemis armenian women's journal. beylerian accepted submissions not only from famous writers but from armenian women throughout the diaspora. she was especially interested in the role armenian women would play in the development of national identity. editorals authored by beylerian explored several women's rights themes
column2: including motherhood. she believed women's education and employment were central to armenian national development. #istanbul #istanbulüniversitesi #turkiye #alexandria #rmenia #ermeniler #vangölü #armenian #feminist #susanbanthony #metoo #genocide #bibleverse #bible #armenianchurch djibin;;en;#istanbul

column1: it’s usually a sign displayed outside of a business that communicates a specific message:  same business but under different leadership.  if i could wear a sign on me that says exactly that i’d be all in cuz i am the same person...i’m just under new management.  i’ve stopped letting my thoughts and actions be controlled by the opinions of others
column3: and by the limitations i’ve placed on myself.  i’m now trying to let my life be inspired by my dreams
column5: and the love i give and receive from those that matter most.

column1: i think it’s important for you to tell your story
column2: to share it with the world but i also think it’s more important to tell your story to yourself.  and you get to choose what that story’s about.  is it the one muddied up with doubt
column4: and the approval of others...or is it the one that lets people know you may look like the same person but you are very much different...you are under new management. .

column1: p.s.  my daughter made this crown for me sometime back and maybe i still put it on...a lot...because duh 🙄

column2: i was also raped. you never think it will happen to you. but it does. you’re terrified to report it because nobody will believe you. i didn’t report it for 7 days. i talked to a few good friends about what happened that night
column3: because i didn’t want to cry rape and have it be a misunderstanding. my amazing friends told me my feelings were valid. i told my mom. a week later. she was amazing and gentle and just held me and we cried. when we got to the police station the nightmare got worse. he asked me “what were you wearing” i told him i was wearing skinny jeans that fit me awkwardly cuz i was chubby and short and a white t-shirt. he asked what underwear i was wearing and if you could see my bra through my shirt. i described exactly how i looked. then he asked me “did you say no?” i looked at the officer and said “i told him to stop and that i didn’t want to and that my mom wouldn’t be proud of me” and officer looked at me and then said something unthinkable. “so you didn’t tell him to stop.” my heart dropped and everything crumbled again. i lost faith in everyone. it’s coming up on two years next month
column4: and i want to raise some awareness. rape is real. stop means no. and men can be raped too. if any of you want to talk privately about this or share your stories
column5: please message my personal @jaynilynne nobody deserves to live in fear. what you wear doesn’t give consent. someone who walks around naked does not have any less right to consent than someone in a snow suit. please tell someone if you’ve been harassed. #metoo -jayni🌵🌻;;en;#metoo;@jaynilynne;;;;0;;the.bumble.project;The Bumble Project;;0;False;1;0;0;19;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/f4190420203047d05eb1eb68cb405011/5D178220/t51.2885-15/e35/45311265_2178972188813882_3396380692905461942_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;as most people know

column1: 132588;instagram;2018-11-28 05:22:30;FALSE;"so incredibly honoured & humbled to have been part of this conversation today talking about issues near & dear to my heart with some brilliant feminist leaders & advocates from un women & the senate of canada. i also had the chance to reconnect with the ed of unwomen
column3: whom i had the pleasure of working alongside on the gender equality advisory council for canada’s g7 presidency. tackling sexual violence & gender based violence on our campuses is critical to ensuring that young people everywhere are supported
column5: & believed. activism around this issue is what brought me to where i am today
column6: and i am always so reflective & in awe of where life has taken me. as a queer & non binary survivor of sexual assault
column7: it’s always been hard to see myself reflected in anything
column8: and finding advocates on campus who were dealing with the same issues i did is what truly saved my life.

column4: & over stretched. we could’nt be here without you! we have so much work to do

column3: or ever ever ever teach the history of yoga
column4: then you need to go listen to @jbrownyoga’s new interview with karen rain
column5: who was an early devotee of pattabhi jois
column6: and whose refusal to be silent about the sexual assault she suffered under his tutelage is changing the face of ashtanga. that’s her there in the headstand at left
column7: in this 1993 @yogaworks primary series video. next to her are richard freeman and tim miller
column8: who went on to become ashtanga icons. why didn’t she? because she was so traumatized by sexual assault at the hands of her “guru” that she left her beloved practice completely
column9: a troubling abusive pattern many fellow mysore practitioners witnessed and never called out.

column1: the bottom line is that the vinyasa practice we know and love is largely a product of a serial sexual predator. gah. seriously. 🤦🏽‍♀️ so if you teach yoga history (especially to starry-eyed newbie teachers!) and leave this shit out
column2: you are lying to your students. and doing a disservice to everyone who will ever study with them.

column1: the shadow side of yoga is real. it’s not pretty and it’s not fun to talk about. but karen does a powerful job here of sharing her story
column3: and saying it like it is
column4: even when it’s uncomfortable. her voice shakes. listening
column5: i feel her vulnerability and her bravery. and i recommit to telling the truth about the often-misogynistic history of yoga
column6: even when it feels icky and uncomfortable.

column2: a new youtube series from the artidote in collaboration with @under25official and @trijog. on this first episode
column3: @harnidhk and i sit to have a vulnerably honest conversation about finding safety in a #metoo world.

column2: the #metoo movement exploded in india. coincidentally
column3: i happened to be in the country running the artidote india tour when distraught and hurt-filled messages from some artidotees first made me aware of the news.

column1: the stories of sexual harassment and abuse against women sent shockwaves of ptsd through survivors across the country. it immediately became an unavoidable
column2: collective conversation — and an extremely important one — on and off the internet. from my instagram inbox to some of the artidote moments that i hosted
column3: anxious questions came in: where do i find safety in a world that feels so unsafe? how can i ever trust a man again? what if someone that i know is a sexual predator?

column1: i also had my own questions: what is my responsibility? as a man? as a friend?  how can i improve in being a safe space for others — both as a person and with the artidote?
so when i had the opportunity to meet @harnidhk
column2: poet and an overall powerhouse of a humane being

column2: a new youtube series from the artidote in collaboration with @under25official and @trijog. on this first episode
column3: @harnidhk and i sit to have a vulnerably honest conversation about finding safety in a #metoo world.

column2: the #metoo movement exploded in india. coincidentally
column3: i happened to be in the country running the artidote india tour when distraught and hurt-filled messages from some artidotees first made me aware of the news.

column1: the stories of sexual harassment and abuse against women sent shockwaves of ptsd through survivors across the country. it immediately became an unavoidable
column2: collective conversation — and an extremely important one — on and off the internet. from my instagram inbox to some of the artidote moments that i hosted
column3: anxious questions came in: where do i find safety in a world that feels so unsafe? how can i ever trust a man again? what if someone that i know is a sexual predator?

column1: i also had my own questions: what is my responsibility? as a man? as a friend?  how can i improve in being a safe space for others — both as a person and with the artidote?

column2: given by brooke axtell @brookeaxtell at the 57th grammy awards inspired me and resonated deeply as truth. let these words wash over you and inspire you to reclaim your worth and express your power to create a more compassionate world. “my name is brooke axtell and i am a survivor of domestic violence. after a year of passionate romance with a handsome
column4: i was stunned when he began to abuse me. i believed he was lashing out because he was in pain
column5: and needed help. i believed my compassion could restore him and our relationship. my empathy was used against me. i was terrified of him and ashamed i was in this position. what bound me to him was my desire to heal him. my compassion was incomplete because it did not include me. when he threatened to kill me
column6: i knew i had to escape. i revealed the truth to my mom and she encouraged me to seek help at a local domestic violence shelter. this conversation saved my life. authentic love does not devalue another human being. authentic love does not silence
column8: or abuse. if you are in a relationship with someone who does not honor or respect you
column9: i want you to know that you are worthy of love. please reach out for help. your voice will save you. let it extend into the night. let it part the darkness. let it set you free to know who you truly are. valuable. beautiful. loved.”";;en;#givingtuesday

column1: they can immediately dispose of the calf

column3: but this is an expensive and rarely chosen option.

column2: even when i shared the story of everything else. how could i ever admit that i had even felt some weird sort of pleasure when after the abuse he grabbed me again and touched me in my private parts? how could i admit i smiled at him when he told crude joke? who in their right mind would do that?

even after forgiving myself for having worn a mini skirt and lipstick the few days before the event - which in my young head made me to blame for the attack - i could not understand or forgive myself for those later moments.

column1: until today. when completely out of the blue it dawned on me: of course! it was the stockholm syndrome! i finally understood it. not just with my mind
column3: physical level. it was like my muscles were softening from a shock they kept for years
column4: as peace flooded my body. i had been in shock and survival mode! it was a coping mechanism that had allowed me to keep my sanity. and today i am so thankful that i had it to protect my young raw mind and emotions. now i understand that those feelings and actions attenuated the shock and trauma i was in and it is thanks to them that i was not scarred more deeply. not just understand
column5: but feel it in every cell of my being.

column1: 132834;instagram;2018-11-28 00:39:22;FALSE;"if you only read one nonfiction book this year
column2: make it this one. big call
column4: but #eggshellskull by @bri.e.lee is really that important. in this memoir
column5: bri tells of her time as a judge’s associate in the district court
column6: where she travelled around metro and regional queensland hearing cases that largely involved sexual assault
column7: mostly committed by men against women they knew
column8: or children in their care. she watched as the system failed vulnerable women and children time and time again. the injustices that she witnessed
column9: cried over and raged against every day finally forced her to confront her own past
column10: and inspired her to bring a claim against her own abuser. armed not just with knowledge of the law
column11: but with a fierce desire to stand up for every woman and child who is abused
column13: discriminated against and victimised on a daily basis
column14: this is the story of how bri finds a fire within herself and learns to wield it like a goddamn hero.

column2: this was a tough read. i was horrified
column6: not just at the perpetrators themselves
column7: but at the people and the system who excused their crimes and ignored the victims’ pleas for help. but it was so inspiring
column8: and so very powerful. i can’t even imagine the courage and strength it took bri not just to bring her claim
column9: but to then write about it and tell the whole world. it is incredibly well researched
column10: and sheds some much needed light on the imbalance of power in the legal industry and the double standards that exist everywhere in our daily lives. bri writes with sensitivity
column11: ferocity and an intensity that meant i devoured this book in one sitting. it is heartbreaking
column14: unflinchingly honest and so very brave. this book will make you think
column16: and make you want to do better. this is a book that everyone should read – especially men
column17: and especially those in the legal industry.

column1: please read this book. get mad. get frustrated. cry if you need to. and then
column3: pick yourself up and get to work. thank you bri for this powerful

#2019yearofreadingwomen;@bri.e.lee;;;;0;;katie.reads.things;Katie 📚;;0;False;30;0;0;257;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/a6be6153fe66d8eb2e5fc57bcbcee7fd/5D1E8C17/t51.2885-15/e35/45313142_743741699305896_3539401731520722978_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"if you only read one nonfiction book this year
column4: make it this one. big call
column6: but #eggshellskull by @bri.e.lee is really that important. in this memoir
column7: bri tells of her time as a judge’s associate in the district court
column8: where she travelled around metro and regional queensland hearing cases that largely involved sexual assault
column9: mostly committed by men against women they knew
column10: or children in their care. she watched as the system failed vulnerable women and children time and time again. the injustices that she witnessed
column11: cried over and raged against every day finally forced her to confront her own past
column12: and inspired her to bring a claim against her own abuser. armed not just with knowledge of the law
column13: but with a fierce desire to stand up for every woman and child who is abused
column15: discriminated against and victimised on a daily basis
column16: this is the story of how bri finds a fire within herself and learns to wield it like a goddamn hero.

column2: this was a tough read. i was horrified
column6: not just at the perpetrators themselves
column7: but at the people and the system who excused their crimes and ignored the victims’ pleas for help. but it was so inspiring
column8: and so very powerful. i can’t even imagine the courage and strength it took bri not just to bring her claim
column9: but to then write about it and tell the whole world. it is incredibly well researched
column10: and sheds some much needed light on the imbalance of power in the legal industry and the double standards that exist everywhere in our daily lives. bri writes with sensitivity
column11: ferocity and an intensity that meant i devoured this book in one sitting. it is heartbreaking
column14: unflinchingly honest and so very brave. this book will make you think
column16: and make you want to do better. this is a book that everyone should read – especially men
column17: and especially those in the legal industry.

column2: violated or vulnerable. in all cases it was a man acting inappropriately - both verbal and/or physical with the first one happening when i was only about 12. shockingly
column3: most of those incidents have occurred in the past 12 months and i feel an increasing weight on my shoulders. it’s not about that comment
column4: or that touch while passing by
column5: but it’s about the wider scope and massive impact this behaviour has on victims and i can’t help but need to make things clear:

column1: it is not ok to touch a colleague’s hips while they squeeze through the door (which you purposely block). it is also not ok to talk about your genitals and what you do with them all day every day - particularly in a professional environment. it is not ok to make any inappropriate references and associations regarding hair colour
column2: age and sex and it is also not ok to completely disregard personal space. unfortunately
column3: women seem to be most subject to become a victim of this behaviour. the fact that a woman smiles at you or is nice to you does not give you the permission to touch her wherever and however. i don’t understand why people think it’s acceptable and sadly…get away with it because most women end feeling the guilty party as has been the case with me as well. the #metoomovement has delivered a very important message and reached many people
column4: but the conversation has gone too quiet again. the level of general awareness needs to increase. to everyone who is experiencing a situation like this. please don’t give in to that feeling of shame and insecurity that is naturally arising. if you don’t feel safe and comfortable to speak up to that particular person
column5: please reach out to someone you trust and don’t shy away to express your feelings. also
column6: don’t find excuses for that person. there is never an excuse for it and the more we talk about it the better.

column1: #repost @rachelmeyeryoga — hey yoga teachers: if you teach vinyasa
column3: or ever ever ever teach the history of yoga
column4: then you need to go listen to @jbrownyoga’s new interview with karen rain
column5: who was an early devotee of pattabhi jois
column6: and whose refusal to be silent about the sexual assault she suffered under his tutelage is changing the face of ashtanga. that’s her there in the headstand at left
column7: in this 1993 @yogaworks primary series video. next to her are richard freeman and tim miller
column8: who went on to become ashtanga icons. why didn’t she? because she was so traumatized by sexual assault at the hands of her “guru” that she left her beloved practice completely
column9: a troubling abusive pattern many fellow mysore practitioners witnessed and never called out.

column1: the bottom line is that the vinyasa practice we know and love is largely a product of a serial sexual predator. gah. seriously. 🤦🏽‍♀️ so if you teach yoga history (especially to starry-eyed newbie teachers!) and leave this shit out
column2: you are lying to your students. and doing a disservice to everyone who will ever study with them.

column1: the shadow side of yoga is real. it’s not pretty and it’s not fun to talk about. but karen does a powerful job here of sharing her story
column3: and saying it like it is
column4: even when it’s uncomfortable. her voice shakes. listening
column5: i feel her vulnerability and her bravery. and i recommit to telling the truth about the often-misogynistic history of yoga
column6: even when it feels icky and uncomfortable.

column1: we owe it to our students. be brave. do the hard work. they deserve the truth. it’s more than just rainbows and unicorns. 🦄🌈

column1: 132919;instagram;2018-11-27 16:58:34;FALSE;"understanding the suppression of the feminine in the past can help us prevent it in the future. 🏛⠀⠀

today i visited some of the best preserved roman ruins in southern spain. i love exploring the remnants of civilisations and tuning into what life must have been like before social media and twerking.
my favourite part was the temple to the goddesses. but though the remnants of the columns may seem like encouraging proof of a culture that venerated the feminine
column2: to me they were stark reminders of a violent suppression.

column1: columns began as symbols of dominance. they represent phallic superiority. in ancient greece
column2: when apollo discovered that there were women from a matrifocal lineage that could communicate with the divine
column4: and guide lost travellers back on their way
column5: he wanted their power for himself. ⠀⠀

column1: he took ownership of the priestesses and erected columns over the land they used to work on freely. colo(m)nising the women... ⠀⠀

column2: these are symbols of a patriarchal system that is not to be blamed on men
column3: but that is important to recognise in order to change and prevent in the future.

column1: what i'm about to share in the next 3 posts is going to be intense.

intense for me and probably intense for you. it's not going to be pretty and it took me a long time to decide to start sharing some of the dark stuff that i had in my life.  i do not do it to be consoled or pitied
column2: i do not do it to get attention.

column1: i share because i'm out of the shadows. i made peace with myself and am so happy in my life like i never could've imagined.
i share for the little 16 year old who was lost and scared and didn't know what to do with herself.
i share for the women who still carry the abuse in their bodies and think and live in the fear of being a victim again.

column2: let's hold on to our hats and begin... today another layer peeled off. cliff was telling me how he had thought of me all day and what an amazing woman i am. jokingly i asked: ""are you sure you're not just experiencing a stockholm syndrome?""

column1: and then it hit me. a big pressure realeased from deep inside as i sighed ""of course! i was experiencing the stockholm syndrome!"" .
when i was 16 i was sexually abused by an uncle in law. it was not rape but he came very close and only stopped because he knew i was a virgin. we were in italy
column2: on his bosses land in the middle of nowhere. after he stopped
column3: i managed to run away and hide in a tree. he came looking for me but couldn't find me and stopped right beneath the tree i was in. i was so emotionally hurt i can't yet put it into words. i had never before experienced such hate or such a scarring feeling of repulsion... but then
column4: i saw the look on his face and for a moment i experienced deep compassion for him. i can now compare the feeling i had to that of a mother who sees a little boy lost and scared and in pain. because that's what he looked like. he then noticed me and my hate was back. but not quick enough. he saw the pity and took advantage of it enough to have me climb down. and with puppy eyes and a teary voice he told me how sorry he was and how he was in love with me. 42 he was and me 16... #raiseyourvibration #highvibetribe #spiritjunkie #selfgrowth #positiveliving #peacewithin #amazinglife #littlestoriesofmylife #stories";;en;#metoo

column1: 132974;instagram;2018-11-27 21:29:10;TRUE;;"went out for 8 comfortable miles and did it. my body is getting faster organically.  it’s not a quick process. i have learned to fall in love with it though. to keep my passion for running i have to practice self preservation. remember why i run and honor the joy it adds to my life. respect my body and appreciate all it’s doing and has done. finding your balance and nurturing your needs is tough- these are always changing. keeping your mind open and being kind you yourself helps. being empathetic and understanding of yourself in the past and in the now. some things take time
column2: you are worthy of that time. i hope you know that. remember quick fixes usually don’t stick.. learn to enjoy the journey ...and remember to smile ❤️ whatever it is.. whatever you want...you can do this.. keep moving forward.  #oymambassador #hairstylist  #inkedgirl #explantista #marathoner #procompressionambassador #runnersrepost  #poweryourpassion  #noexcuses #runspiration #strength #runnerscommunity #motherrunner #getafterit #girlswholift

column1: 132977;instagram;2018-11-27 21:30:36;FALSE;"a preview (this is just a quick snapshot & not a final work) of a new series that i've been working on with the working titles ""stolen flowers"" & ""flowers from homes"". what is your preferred title for this series?
i started this series to help engage my mind and body in learning to walk again. first in a rehabilitation centre
column2: and then back at home - starting with walking just past one house and back
column3: and now up to 5km at a time. sometimes i can manage walking my wonder dog sebastian ❤. thinking about why i started the series and why i titled it stolen flowers is related to the #metoo hashtag that went viral earlier in the year. my past has been littered with damaging
column4: secretive and painful events starting at an innocent and sheltered version of me at 16yo. when i first tried to speak out about what had happened to me to a psychologist and psychiatrist
column6: pain and inability to process the events as being a drug user & at the time i felt a huge betrayal of privacy as they shared this with my then school and my parents. the experience further damaged my soul and belief in the medical system. it took a long time to trust a psychologist
column7: men and those close to me
column8: let alone share snippets of these painful events.

column1: flowers have long been metaphors for innocence
column2: sexuality and loss of innocence. sometimes the act of ripping or cutting a flower from its plant is a deflowering
column4: a cause of its inability to play a part in the plants future reproduction - a crack in the lifecycle.

column5: unadulterated joy in photographing these small natural miracles
column6: having their scent pervade a room
column7: and carefully arranging them to be lifted up as life symbols.

column1: i hope you enjoy this series - i have a few working photos to share while i'm in post-production of this series.

column3: like premarital sex being interrupted by myers
column4: or characters only being in the movie for the sole purpose of being killed by myers. there’s also some social subtext to halloween relating to the #metoo movement. three generations of the strohd women have been dealing with the trauma of michael myers ruining their family
column6: they’re rising up and saying “no more
column7: ” finally getting rid of the abusive man in their life (e.g. micheal myers). the only gripes i have with halloween is that there are some really dumb decisions made in the movie where it just makes you roll your eyes
column8: and they call back a bit too much to the original film. and of course
column9: jamie lee curtis is amazing in the movie. overall
